  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And he took the damsel by the hand,....  See Gill on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 9:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And said unto her; in the Syriac language, which was then commonly spoken by the Jews, and well understood: hence the Syriac version expresses the following words without an interpretation, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Talitha Cumi. The Ethiopic version reads it, \"Tabitha Cumi\"; and so do some Greek copies, and Latin versions, taking it to be the same word as in Acts 9:36 whereas that signifies \"Dorcas, a roe\"; but this word is of another signification, as here explained, ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Talitha Cumi. The Ethiopic version reads it, \"Tabitha Cumi\"; and so do some Greek copies, and Latin versions, taking it to be the same word as in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 9:36",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " whereas that signifies \"Dorcas, a roe\"; but this word is of another signification, as here explained, ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "which is, being interpreted, damsel (I say unto thee) arise. The phrase, \"I say unto thee\", is no part of the interpretation of the above Syriac words; but is added, by the evangelist, as being what was expressed by Christ at the same time, signifying his authority and power over death; only \"damsel arise\", is the interpretation of them,  \"Tali\", signifies a \"boy\", and  \"Talitha\", a \"girl\"; and so they are often used in the Targums (w), and in the Talmud: the one is used for a boy of seventeen years of age (x), and the other for a girl of sixteen or seventeen years of age (y); so that this child might well be called by this name, since she was but twelve years of age; and  \"Cumi\", is the imperative  \"to arise\". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(w) Targum Hieres in Deuteronomy 22.21. & Targum Sheni in Esther ii. 9. (x) T. Bab. Bava Bathra, fol. 142. 2. Gloss. in ib. (y) lb. fol. 91. 2.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(w) Targum Hieres in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 22",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".21. & Targum Sheni in Esther ii. 9. (x) T. Bab. Bava Bathra, fol. 142. 2. Gloss. in ib. (y) lb. fol. 91. 2.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
