  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 41.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The house was now set free from the perfunctory and noisy crowd; and he goes up to the dead child, and takes her by the hand and says, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Talitha cumi",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; literally ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Little maid",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "arise.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The evangelist gives the words in the very language used by our Lord - the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ipsissima verba",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", remembered no doubt and recorded by St. Peter; just as he gives \"Ephphatha\" in another miracle. Mark 5:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
